# Sequential edits with review

When a task requires changes in **multiple files**:

1. **One file per step** — Apply edits to a **single** file, then stop. Do not edit additional files in the same turn unless the user has approved and asked to continue.
2. **Summarize before moving on** — After each file change, briefly describe **what** changed and **why**, and point to the file path (and use code citations when helpful). Treat this as a checkpoint for review.
3. **Wait for go-ahead** — Do not start the next file until the user confirms they are happy with the current change (e.g. “looks good”, “continue”, or specific follow-up on that file).
4. **Large refactors** — Same rule: one file, review, then the next—even if that makes the overall task take several rounds.

**Exceptions** (only when the user explicitly asks):

- “Change all of these in one go” or “batch the edits”
- Trivial paired edits the user already approved as a set (e.g. rename across two files after agreeing on the rename)

If unsure whether to batch, default to **one file + review**.
